            <person xml:id="pers1073">
               <p>A native of <placeName>County Down, Ireland</placeName>, Horner entered the <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerancy</seg> in <date when="1770">1770</date> (see <hi
                     rend="italic">Works</hi>, 10:397). He remained in
                     <placeName>Ireland</placeName> for his first few appointments, but he served
                  broadly throughout <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName>&apos;s life and was the recipient of one of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s last surviving letters.
                  Horner married <persName>Amey Gregory</persName> in <date when="1783">1783</date>,
                  and their son <persName>William George Horner</persName> (<date from="1784"
                     to="1837">1784–1837</date>) was a mathematician who served for a time as
                  headmaster of Kingswood School.</p>
            </person>
